1 Introduction

This is an implementation of a support vector machine designed to identify short-term stock price changes, based on previous stock parameters: open, low, high, close, volume

1.1 Stock selected for this exercise:

I selected Tailored Brands because I wanted to see if the stock performed well or not. I had a friend that recommended purchasing this stock. I purchase and sold the stock in a short period of time. I think I may have sold too soon and am interested to see how the stock performed.

picture of the stock price

HP price

Names of variables in TLRD data set price.open price.high price.low price.close volume price.adjusted ret.adjusted.prices ret.closing.prices avg.change change

1.3 classification model, categorical response

1.3.1 traditional interface:

x <- subset(TLRDDataFrame, select = -change)
y <- TLRDDataFrame[1:371,]$change
model1 <- svm(x, y) 

#model1 is all the data 
print(model1)
##

2 train and test set:

pctTrain=0.70   # use about 70% of the the data 
nObs = length(x[,1])
nObs = 371
nTrain = round(pctTrain*nObs,0)

# next line take data in order
#TrainSetIndex = 1:nTrain

# take these lines as a random sample 
scramble = sample(1:nObs)
TrainSetIndex = scramble[1:nTrain]
TestSetIndex = scramble[(nTrain+1):nObs]

3.1.2 Use this template to get the SVM:

  1. Training and Test sets:

Random selecton from the stock data to get the training set, 70% used. Remaining 30% of obersvations used for the test set. Random used so that dates or an unexpected drop within a time frame does not effect the model as much since the % selects at random.

  1. How well did the SVM do?

My SVM performed well. I only didn’t predict the over 2 times, even 7 times, and under 3 times.

knitr::include_graphics("pred2.png")

After my adjustements on prediction 3. Predicted over was only incorrect 2 timse, even four times, and under 1 time.

knitr::include_graphics(“pred2.png”)

knitr::include_graphics("pred3.png")

  1. Tune the algorithm- i.e. find optimal gamma and cost values.

After the model was tuned using a gamma of 1 and cost of 0.5, my prediction percentage increased.
